_exec_summary.SummaryText:
A Risk Management Program (RMP) has been implemented at Day-Glo Color Corp.'s Twinsburg facility for the reduction of accidental releases of hazardous materials. The RMP summaries the management, administrative, procedural, and technological controls that works together to minimize the risk to the community of hazardous chemical releases. The Risk Management Plan is organized to correspond with specific U.S. Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) RMP definitions and requirements, including:
- Introduction;
- Facility and regulated substances identification;
- Hazard Assessment;
- Prevention Program;
- Five-Year Accident History;
- Emergency Response Plan; and
- Planned changes to improve safety.

Introduction
Risk management and safety are important concerns at Day-Glo Color. This RMP formalizes and documents these activities. Day-Glo Color is committed to conducting its operations in a safe and responsible manner and to reducing risks to human health and to the environment.

Facility and Regulated Substance Identification
Day-Glo Color Corp. owns and operates a color pigment manufacturing plant in Twinsburg, Ohio. Cyclohexylamine (CHA), a regulated toxic RMP chemical substance with a threshold quantity for accidental release prevention of 15,000 pounds, is used as an ingredient in the manufacture of color pigments. The maximum amount of CHA present in the system is approximately 30,000 pounds (4,200 gallons). The normal amount present is less than about 20,000 pounds (2,750 gallons).

Hazard Assessment : Worst Case Scenario (WCS)
The worst-case toxic accidental release scenario assumes the entire contents of the single 7,500 gallon CHA storage tank are released into the storage tank containment dike and evaporates at a rate of approximately 10 lb./min. EPA's SLAB guidance shows that under the worst-case weather conditions the release could travel 0.4 miles downwind until the toxic endpoint is reached.

